column6: $3.43 today and yesterday, is right in the middle of one of the bands.
Spot market is down 4 pct after FEDs' rate decision.

Looking at EIA data, gas price on mid-week Feb is usually within 25 cents of the price at the start of the year. (I didn't break out a calculator for that math, just rough math.) So, looking at the current AAA price, the brackets fall right around 3.20. EIA data: https://www.eia.gov/dnav/pet/hist/LeafHandler.ashx?n=pet&s=emm_epm0_pte_nus_dpg&f=w
Initial forecast using the same method as the same question for the longer range of 3 July 2023 taking into account the following:
3.50 because everyone is worried about the statutes quo
Setting the current price as the baseline. Prices could go in either direction from here, but more likely to fall than rise.
Oil companies have no interest in increasing production swiftly. They did this in the past and got burned. They will be riding this wave as much as possible.
Looking at the EIA charts from the other gas price question, it looks like the March price of gas can be 20 to 30 cents up OR down from the prior year's Nov price.
Diesel shortage causing end point shipping issues and/or a refinery event will be the greatest likely variables. (More than OPEC+)
Over the next few months we have competing items.
